<br>
Wings are fun, but a pain, for a few reasons.<br>
<br>
First: the only skinned wings are a bat's.  Ever see a bat's wings?  They go all the way to the feet.  Same for all those flying dinosaurs.  Makes every dragon you've ever seen wrong.<br>
<br>
Second: Bats are small.  And light.  The wings don't need to be incredibly large.  And the pteranadon?  As big as those guys were, they weighed in at around 25 lbs.  So wings that need to carry people, let alone dragons, need to be gigantic.  I always thought it would look kinda cool if someone did an accurate pic, although you probably couldn't pack on enough muscle to get them to work right.<br>
<br>
Third:  Arms and wings are homologous structures, which means your forelimbs took the wing evolution path or the arm evolution path.  So, you really can't have wings AND arms.  This pisses me off because it means there's really no &quot;correct&quot; place to put the wings on a dragon if it has arms.<br>
<br>
Fourth: Ever consider how wings on people would look.  We wouldn't suddenly become reptilian for the wing portion (we'll ignore that no reptiles, to my knowledge, have wings).  It'd be all skinny, or hairy.  Eck...<br>
<br>
Those aren't necessarily crits, but instead random snippets of knowledge, because I enjoy talking about wings.  Okay then, onto the pics.<br>
<br>
First pic:  The wings' &quot;fingers&quot; don't start at the dragon's body, but it looks like you picked that up in the next pick.  Make sure the dragon's fore arms attach appropriately, right now, it look like your dragon's right forearms attaches too far up the spine.  Well, it shouldn't even attach to the spine, there're shoulders for that, so I guess the shoulders are too far forward.<br>
<br>
Second:  pay attention to the concavity of the parts of the wing.  Your top finger starts concave up, when it should be down (concave up holds water, down doesn't).  Nothing too much about the others.  You might consider drawing them larger so you make sure you know what's going on (not only that, but as you get larger, you get more space for details and don't end up fighting yourself for room).<br>
<br>
Third: I always thought goat legs (or any legs with two main joints) were sort of like human legs, except the two main joints are shorter, more angled at rest, and the bottom third is just an extended foot with more defined to structures.  Maybe I'm wrong, I dunno, I can never do em anyway.  It'd be a bit pretentious to comment on the rest of the anatomy, as it looks like you're on your way.  Anatomy's annoying because you need to remember a ton of muscles before you finally get it to start looking right.  That's why i always have tons of clothes ;).  Woo laziness.<br>
<br>
Anyway, good job.  All that stuff about wings being impossible doesn't mean I don't like dragons or people with wings.  I really do in fact.  It's just that the impossibility of their existence irks me.  That and I suck at drawing them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=j3t@polykarbonbbs>J3T</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/26/03 12:36:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm23.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8709.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Dragons, talons and demons</span><hr size=1> thanks for taking the time to reply like that, i really appreciate it. <br>
